---
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../config/site';
import SiteLayout from '../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';
---

<SiteLayout
  title={`${SITE_TITLE} FAQ`}
  description="Answers to common questions about bangs.to in plain English."
  currentPath="/faq"
>
  <div class="grid gap-4 lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,0.72fr)_minmax(0,1fr)]">
    <aside class="card h-fit p-5 sm:p-6">
      <p class="text-xs font-700 uppercase tracking-[0.24em] text-primary-700">Trust notes</p>
      <h1
        class="mt-2 font-display text-[2.4rem] font-800 leading-tight tracking-[-0.04em] text-text sm:text-[2.8rem]"
      >
        FAQ
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-text-secondary">
        Short answers to most of your common questions.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-4 grid gap-3">
        <div class="rounded-[20px] bg-bg-soft p-4">
          <p class="text-sm font-700 text-text">What is this?</p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-text-secondary">
            Bangs.to is a search redirect tool, allowing you to search the web with !bangs, fast.
            All redirection happens client-side, your search queries never leave your device and no
            information passes through bangs.to.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-[20px] bg-bg-soft p-4">
          <p class="text-sm font-700 text-text">How is this an improvement over DuckDuckGo?</p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-text-secondary">
            DuckDuckGo does their redirects server side. Their DNS is ... not always great. This
            means that it often takes ages and ages to get to your results. Instead of the slow
            round-trip to their servers, we do all the work client-side.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-[20px] bg-bg-soft p-4">
          <p class="text-sm font-700 text-text">Why does this exist?</p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-text-secondary">
            Years of using DuckDuckGo and Kagi has conditioned me into a !bangs user. I admit I have
            a bit of a problem, because I now cannot search the web without !bangs. <a
              href="https://duckduckgo.com/"
              target="_blank">DuckDuckGo</a
            > resolves search results very very slowly, so I scratched my own itch.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </aside>

    <div class="grid gap-4">
      <section class="card">
        <h2 class="section-title mb-2">What is ban.gs?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          ban.gs is a shortcut search tool. It lets you type things like
          <code>!gh react</code> to search GitHub, <code>!w cats</code> to search Wikipedia, or just plain
          words for a normal web search.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="card">
        <h2 class="section-title mb-2">What is a !bang?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          A !bang is a short code that starts with <code>!</code>. It tells bangs.to where to send
          your search. For example,
          <code>!yt ambient music</code> searches <a
            href="https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=ambient%20music"
            target="_blank">YouTube</a
          > for <code>ambient music</code> and
          <code>!mdn fetch</code> searches <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/" target="_blank"
            >MDN</a
          > for <code>fetch</code>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="card">
        <h2 class="section-title mb-2">Does bangs.to see everything I search for?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          No. Your browser does the redirection and your queries never leave your device. There is
          no analytics or tracking built into the site.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="card">
        <h2 class="section-title mb-2">Do I need to install an extension?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          No browser extension is required. You visit the site once, then add it as a custom search
          engine in your browser. After that, your address bar can use it directly.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="card">
        <h2 class="section-title mb-2">What happens if I type a normal search?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          If you do not use a !bang, bangs.to sends the search to your default search engine.
          Normally this default is <a href="https://duckduckgo.com/" target="_blank">DuckDuckGo</a>,
          but you can change it in <a href="#settings">Settings</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="card">
        <h2 class="section-title mb-2">Can I change the default search engine?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          Yes. Open Settings and change the default bang. That decides where plain searches go when
          you do not type a shortcut.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="card">
        <h2 class="section-title mb-2">Is this private?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          It is more private than sending every search through a remote redirect page, because the
          redirect logic runs on your device. But the site you end up using, like DuckDuckGo,
          Google, YouTube, or GitHub, still receives the search you send to it.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>
